<font color="#FF0000">WITH HIGH HOPES WE START ANEW</font><br>
<tt>Tue Dec  2 23:01:54 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
It is with hopes high, that we can re-emerge from the winter of our discontent, the hibernation of our intellect, and began anew to discuss and debate the issues, rather than the personalities, something that almost destroyed this site.<br><br>
I cast no stones, nor do I wish to receive any.  I respect this site, I have actually come to viewing it as the living memorial to all sides of the thing, this horrible &quot;thing&quot; called the Viet Nam War, American Involvement. I do not care to discuss the role of the French, or the Chinese, or others, only the role this &quot;war&quot; played on my American generation (the 60's) and on my country (USA).<br><br>
I think it will be hard, but we all can do it if we really try, to get beyond individual and petty hatreds and deal with the real issues that have divided us as a nation, a people, and as individuals still trying to figure out the license plate of the bus that &quot;just&quot; ran us over 40 years ago.<br><br>
I ask all of you to reflect on how it was without this site, and how it is with this site. I for one find my life richer with this place in existence, and I RUN to tell all of you this. Will you join me? Or will you will you just leave? You do not have to destroy it for those of us who like it, you know?<br><br>
We can be mature and adult (GOD most of us are over 50) rational human beiings, of both genders and many races, and talk to each other with respect and kindness. We do not need military jargon, war talk, or peace talk (for that matter), nor do we need any splinter cliques (small seperate groups working against the goodness of the whole), we can all be spokes of the common wheel. That wheel being the USA's involvement in SouthEast Asia in the 60's and 70's, and maybe before and after that, and how it impacted our generation and each of us individually.<br><br>
I pray all of you will reflect and agree with this assessment, for I fear the next time we are closed will be the last time, and the golden opportunity to talk, not to win, to debate, not to win, will be lost. History is the only winner allowed, we are merely the chessboard players offering the color commentary, we do not know the right or the wrong, that is for future generations to weigh in on and debate.<br><br>
I shout outloud, SHALOM, to Marc Weiss, our host, &quot;To Life&quot; and I hope we live up to his faith in us. In ALL of us.
